    "::: {.callout-note appearance=\"simple\"}\n",
    "This is preliminary work based on openly available data.\n",
    "It is not an official release and should not be cited as such. ✌️ \n",
    ":::\n",
    "\n",
    "## 🚲 Intro\n",
    "\n",
    "Bike infrastructure is one of the cheapest ways a city can\n",
    "expand who can get around — but only one kind actually works.\n",
    "\n",
    "Painted lanes on busy roads do almost nothing for ridership —\n",
    "[the research on this is settled](URL_TODO).\n",
    "What moves the needle is **high-comfort** infrastructure:\n",
    "physically separated cycle tracks, multi-use paths, and local street \n",
    "bikeways. Places where you don't have to negotiate with a moving car.\n",
    "\n",
    "Between 2019 and 2024, Canadian cities added thousands of kilometres\n",
    "of cycling infrastructure. Not all of it was equal.\n",
    "Not all cities performed equally.\n",
    "\n",
    "Using two releases of the\n",
    "**[Canadian Cycling Network Database (CCND)](URL_TODO)**\n",
    "and the **[Can-BICS](URL_TODO)** classification framework,\n",
    "we measured how access to high-comfort infrastructure changed\n",
    "across three cities: Victoria, Montreal, and Toronto.\n",
    "\n",
    "**TL;DR:** Victoria punches way above its weight.\n",
    "Montreal has made real gains.\n",
    "Toronto has barely moved — despite being Canada's largest city,\n",
    "and despite cycling investment being perpetually promised\n",
    "and perpetually deferred.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 📊 Data\n",
    "\n",
    "The analysis uses two national snapshots of Canadian cycling\n",
    "infrastructure:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **[2019 release](https://health-infobase.canada.ca/datalab/bicycling-infrastructure.html)**\n",
    "  — baseline network, published by the Public Health Agency of Canada\n",
    "- **[2024 release](URL_TODO)**\n",
    "  — five years of additions\n",
    "\n",
    "Each dataset is a collection of line segments — one per stretch of\n",
    "infrastructure — with attributes describing the type of facility."
   ]
